\title{Making it Explicit}
\author{robert-brandom}
\import{macros}


\subtree{\title{Preface}
\p{The work will show a kind of understanding/explanatory power comes from talking about language in this new way (rather than to say that one is rationally \em{obliged} to talk this way).
}
\p{Project: explain the \em{meanings} of linguistic expressions in terms of their \em{use}.
}
\ul{
 \li{ This would be trivial if our vocabulary for talking about use allowed "using the word 'not' to express negation" or "using the term 'Julius Caesar' to refer to Julius Caesar"}
 \li{This would be impossible if our vocabulary for talking about use was restricted to the vocabulary of physics.}
 \li{Brandom will use a \em{normative} vocabulary, understanding norms in terms of \em{commitments} and \em{entitlements}.}
}
\subtree{\title{Chapter summaries}
\ol{
\li{Introduces / motivates normative pragmatics }
\li{Inferential theory of propositional contentfulness}
\li{Part 1 of core theory: A model of the social practice of giving and asking for reasons. A social, linguistic account of \em{intentionality}.}
\li{Part 2 of core theory: A social, linguistic account of \em{perception} and \em{action}.}
\li{The expressive role of traditional representational semantic vocabulary (e.g. 'true' and 'refers').}
\li{Indirect inferential role of singular terms/predicates. Subsitutional analysis which is crucial to understanding how inferentialism can go beyond sentences.}
\li{Anaphora}
\li{Representational dimension of conceptual content}
}
\p{Making something explicit is \em{saying} it: putting it into a form in which it can be given as a reason / have reasons demanded for it. }
\p{Expression is the relation between what is \em{implicit} in what we do and what is \em{explicit} in what we say.
To express something is to make it explicit. }
\p{Two tasks}
\ol{
\li{Explaining (making theoretially explicit) the implicit structure of linguistic practices in virtue of which they count as making anything explicit at all}
\li{Working out a theory of the expressive role distinctive of \em{logical} vocabulary.
	- E.g. conditionals make \em{implicit} inferential commitments \em{explicit}. Negation makes explicit the incompatibility of commitments.}
}
}
\subtree{\title{Aspirations (why the book is long)}
