\p{show how content is related to use}
\p{achieve self-referential expressive completeness}
\p{present a unified vision of language and mind}


\subtree{\title{Toward a Normative Pragmatics}
\subtree{\title{I. Introduction}
\subtree{\title{Saying 'We'}
\p{What is 'we'? How should we demarcate "us" from "them"? This is tantamount to saying who or what we are. It is both discovered as well as decided. We might say there is no \em{right} answer to this, each criterion for demarcation just picks out a different kind of community. One criterion that doesn't feel arbitrary is "X is one of \em{us} if X, like us, X says 'we' (i.e. makes a distinction of \em{us} and \em{them})". However, this just pushes the problem to specifing what one has to do to count as "saying 'we'".
}
}
\subtree{\title{Sapience}
\p{Demarcating 'we' as \em{reasonable} beings:}
\ul{
\li{Our transactions with other things \em{mean} something to us}
\li{they have \em{conceptual content} for us}
\li{We \em{understand} them}
\li{We are bound by a \em{normative} force, a rational 'ought'.}
\li{We are placed in a space of reasons}
}
\p{This would be taking \em{sapience} rather than \em{sentience} as the constellation of characteristics which distinguishes us.
}
\p{Sentience is what we share with non-verbal animals (being aware in the sense of being awake).
}
\p{\em{Reliable, differential responsiveness} is what we share with non-verbal animals and artifacts such as thermostats and land mines.
}
\p{Another characterization of \em{sapience} is focused on truth, rather than inference (like above):
}
\ul{
\li{We are believers, where believing is taking-to-be-true}
\li{We are agents, and acting is making-true}
\li{We have states such as belief/desire/intention which are contentful in the sense that the question can be raised under which circumstances what is believed/desired/intended would be \em{true}.}
\li{We \em{understand} content by grasping the conditions necessary and sufficient for its truth.}}

\p{Both characterizations of sapience try to explain \em{propositions}, which both have truth conditions and stand in inferential relations. These coordinate concepts compete with each other for which should be explained in terms of the other.
}
}
